However, the original Java code doesn't handle exceptions, just catches IOException and does nothing. So in C, perhaps we can ignore error checking as well. So the steps for C:

- Read n from stdin. Use fgets to read a line, then convert to int.

- If n is 1, print "Hello World".

- Else, read two lines, convert each to int, sum, print. Implementing this in C.

So code outline:

#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

int main() {
    char buffer[128]; // Buffer to read lines

    // Read first line (n)
    fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), stdin);
    int n = atoi(buffer);

    if (n == 1) {
        printf("Hello World\n");
    } else {
        // Read next two lines
        int a, b;
        fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), stdin);
        a = atoi(buffer);
        fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), stdin);
        b = atoi(buffer);
        printf("%d\n", a + b);
    }

    return 0;
} Wait, but what if the lines are longer than the buffer size?

